<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-QR-factorization">
  <title><m>QR</m> factorization and least squares</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-qr-definition">
    <title>QR factorization</title>

    <p>
      Recall that a list of vectors is orthonormal when the vectors have length <m>1</m> and are pairwise orthogonal. Also recall the notion of an upper triangular matrix from <xref ref="def-4-1-triangular-matrices"/>.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix with independent columns. A <term>QR factorization</term> of <m>A</m> is an <m>m \times n</m> matrix <m>Q</m>, with orthonormal columns, and an invertible upper triangular <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>R</m>, with positive entries on its diagonal, so that <m>A = QR</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <warning xml:id="warn-u4-rectangular-q">
      <title>Rectangular <m>Q</m></title>
      <p>
        In a <m>QR</m> factorization of an <m>m \times n</m> matrix with <m>m \gt n</m>, the matrix <m>Q</m> has orthonormal columns, so <m>Q^TQ=I_n</m>. But <m>Q</m> is not square, and <m>QQ^T</m> is not usually <m>I_m</m>.
      </p>
    </warning>

    <paragraphs xml:id="bridge-qr-least-squares">
      <title>QR for least squares</title>
      <p>
        Normal equations are conceptually important, but <m>QR</m> is often a better computational method. If <m>A=QR</m> with <m>Q</m> having orthonormal columns, then
        <me>\|A\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{b}\|=\|QR\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{b}\|.</me>
        Orthogonality reduces the least-squares problem to
        <me>R\hat{\mathbf{x}}=Q^T\mathbf{b},</me>
        which is triangular and easier to solve accurately.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <activity xml:id="act-u4-qr-code-reading">
      <title>Reading QR least-squares code</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The following code uses <m>QR</m> to solve the same least-squares problem from the Unit 2 target activity.
        </p>
        <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[A = np.array([
    [1.0, 0.0],
    [0.0, 1.0],
    [1.0, 1.0],
])
b = np.array([1.0, 2.0, 4.0])

Q, R = np.linalg.qr(A)
x_qr = np.linalg.solve(R, Q.T @ b)
x_lstsq = np.linalg.lstsq(A, b, rcond=None)[0]

Q.T @ Q, x_qr, x_lstsq
]]></code></program>
        <ol>
          <li><p>What should <c>Q.T @ Q</c> be close to?</p></li>
          <li><p>Why does the code solve a system with <c>R</c> instead of a system with <c>A</c>?</p></li>
          <li><p>Why should <c>x_qr</c> and <c>x_lstsq</c> agree?</p></li>
          <li><p>Does this mean <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> has an exact solution?</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The matrix <m>Q</m> has orthonormal columns, so <c>Q.T @ Q</c> should be close to the identity matrix. The <m>QR</m> factorization rewrites the least-squares problem using <m>A=QR</m>, which leads to the triangular system
          <me>R\hat{\mathbf{x}}=Q^T\mathbf{b}.</me>
          The vectors <c>x_qr</c> and <c>x_lstsq</c> should agree because they compute the same least-squares solution. This does not mean <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> has an exact solution; it means the fitted vector <m>A\hat{\mathbf{x}}</m> is the closest reachable output.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let
          <me>Q = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \amp -\frac{2}{\sqrt{6}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \end{bmatrix}</me>.
          Check that the columns are orthonormal and compute <m>Q^TQ</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Column 1: <m>\|\mathbf{q}_1\|^2 = \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^2 = \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{3} = 1</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          Column 2: <m>\|\mathbf{q}_2\|^2 = \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\right)^2 + \left(-\frac{2}{\sqrt{6}}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\right)^2 = 1</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          Orthogonality:
          <md>
            <mrow>\mathbf{q}_1 \cdot \mathbf{q}_2 \amp = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \left(-\frac{2}{\sqrt{6}}\right) + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{\sqrt{18}} - \frac{2}{\sqrt{18}} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{18}} = 0</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Compute <m>Q^TQ</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>Q^TQ \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \\ 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \amp -\frac{2}{\sqrt{6}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}
              \end{bmatrix} 
              \begin{bmatrix} 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \\ 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \amp -\frac{2}{\sqrt{6}} \\ 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}
              \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 
                \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{3} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{18}} - \frac{2}{\sqrt{18}} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{18}} \\
                \frac{1}{\sqrt{18}} - \frac{2}{\sqrt{18}} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{18}} \amp \frac{1}{6} + \frac{4}{6} + \frac{1}{6}
                \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 
                  1 \amp 0 \\
                  0 \amp 1
                  \end{bmatrix} = I_2</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </activity>

          <activity>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Solve the linear system <m>R\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m> where
                <me>
                  R = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 2 \amp 7 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} \quad\text{and}\quad \mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 30 \\ 21 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}
                </me>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                For an upper triangular matrix like <m>R</m>, we can solve the system using back-substitution. Starting with the last equation:
                <md>
                  <mrow>2x_3 \amp = 6</mrow>
                  <mrow>x_3 \amp = 3</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
              <p>
                Now substitute this value into the second equation:
                <md>
                  <mrow>3x_2 + 5x_3 \amp = 21</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x_2 + 5(3) \amp = 21</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x_2 + 15 \amp = 21</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x_2 \amp = 6</mrow>
                  <mrow>x_2 \amp = 2</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
              <p>
                Finally, substitute both known values into the first equation:
                <md>
                  <mrow>4x_1 + 2x_2 + 7x_3 \amp = 30</mrow>
                  <mrow>4x_1 + 2(2) + 7(3) \amp = 30</mrow>
                  <mrow>4x_1 + 4 + 21 \amp = 30</mrow>
                  <mrow>4x_1 \amp = 5</mrow>
                  <mrow>x_1 \amp = 1.25</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
              <p>
                  The solution is <m>\mathbf{x} = (1.25, 2, 3)</m>.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </activity>

          <p>
            The QR factorization is a matrix version of the <em>Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization process</em>, which has many applications in many numerical algorithms.
          </p>

          <theorem>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Every <m>m \times n</m> matrix <m>A</m> with linearly independent columns has a QR factorization <m>A = QR</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <proof>
              <p>
                Let <m>A = [\mathbf{c}_1 \mathbf{c}_2 \cdots \mathbf{c}_n]</m> be the matrix with columns <m>\mathbf{c}_1, \mathbf{c}_2, \ldots, \mathbf{c}_n</m>. Apply Gram-Schmidt process to obtain orthogonal vectors <m>\mathbf{f}_1, \mathbf{f}_2, \ldots, \mathbf{f}_n</m> where: <m>\mathbf{f}_1 = \mathbf{c}_1</m> and
                <me>\mathbf{f}_k = \mathbf{c}_k - \frac{\mathbf{c}_k \cdot \mathbf{f}_1}{\|\mathbf{f}_1\|^2}\mathbf{f}_1 - \frac{\mathbf{c}_k \cdot \mathbf{f}_2}{\|\mathbf{f}_2\|^2}\mathbf{f}_2 - \cdots - \frac{\mathbf{c}_k \cdot \mathbf{f}_{k-1}}{\|\mathbf{f}_{k-1}\|^2}\mathbf{f}_{k-1}</me>
                for <m>k = 2, 3, \ldots, n</m>.
              </p>
              <p>
                Let <m>\mathbf{q}_k = \frac{\mathbf{f}_k}{\|\mathbf{f}_k\|}</m> for each <m>k</m>. Then <m>\mathbf{q}_1, \mathbf{q}_2, \ldots, \mathbf{q}_n</m> are orthonormal vectors.
              </p>
              <p>
                We can rewrite each column <m>\mathbf{c}_k</m> as a linear combination of the <m>\mathbf{q}_i</m>: <m>\mathbf{c}_1 = \|\mathbf{f}_1\|\mathbf{q}_1</m>,
                <md>
                  <mrow>\mathbf{c}_2 \amp = (\mathbf{c}_2 \cdot \mathbf{q}_1)\mathbf{q}_1 + \|\mathbf{f}_2\|\mathbf{q}_2</mrow>
                  <mrow>\mathbf{c}_3 \amp = (\mathbf{c}_3 \cdot \mathbf{q}_1)\mathbf{q}_1 + (\mathbf{c}_3 \cdot \mathbf{q}_2)\mathbf{q}_2 + \|\mathbf{f}_3\|\mathbf{q}_3</mrow>
                </md>
                and so on. This gives us the matrix factorization:
                <md>
                  <mrow>A \amp = [\mathbf{c}_1 \mathbf{c}_2 \cdots \mathbf{c}_n]</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = [\mathbf{q}_1 \mathbf{q}_2 \cdots \mathbf{q}_n]
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    \|\mathbf{f}_1\| \amp \mathbf{c}_2 \cdot \mathbf{q}_1 \amp \mathbf{c}_3 \cdot \mathbf{q}_1 \amp \cdots \amp \mathbf{c}_n \cdot \mathbf{q}_1\\
                    0 \amp \|\mathbf{f}_2\| \amp \mathbf{c}_3 \cdot \mathbf{q}_2 \amp \cdots \amp \mathbf{c}_n \cdot \mathbf{q}_2\\
                    0 \amp 0 \amp \|\mathbf{f}_3\| \amp \cdots \amp \mathbf{c}_n \cdot \mathbf{q}_3\\
                    \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots\\
                    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp \|\mathbf{f}_n\|
                    \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                  </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  So <m>A = QR</m> where <m>Q = [\mathbf{q}_1 \mathbf{q}_2 \cdots \mathbf{q}_n]</m> has orthonormal columns and <m>R</m> is upper triangular with positive diagonal entries.
                </p>
              </proof>
            </theorem>

            <activity>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Consider the matrix
                  <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
                  Find its QR factorization.
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  The columns of <m>A</m> are <m>\mathbf{c}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{c}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Set <m>\mathbf{f}_1 = \mathbf{c}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Then <m>\|\mathbf{f}_1\| = \sqrt{3^2 + 4^2} = 5</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Compute <m>\mathbf{q}_1 = \frac{\mathbf{f}_1}{\|\mathbf{f}_1\|} = \frac{1}{5}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{3}{5} \\ \frac{4}{5} \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Compute <m>\mathbf{f}_2 = \mathbf{c}_2 - \frac{\mathbf{c}_2 \cdot \mathbf{f}_1}{\|\mathbf{f}_1\|^2}\mathbf{f}_1</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                  <m>\mathbf{c}_2 \cdot \mathbf{f}_1 = 1 \cdot 3 + 2 \cdot 4 = 11</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                  <m>\mathbf{f}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} - \frac{11}{25}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 - \frac{33}{25} \\ 2 - \frac{44}{25} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{25-33}{25} \\ \frac{50-44}{25} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{8}{25} \\ \frac{6}{25} \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                  Compute <m>\|\mathbf{f}_2\| = \sqrt{(-\frac{8}{25})^2 + (\frac{6}{25})^2} = \sqrt{\frac{64+36}{625}} = \sqrt{\frac{100}{625}} = \frac{10}{25} = \frac{2}{5}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Compute <m>\mathbf{q}_2 = \frac{\mathbf{f}_2}{\|\mathbf{f}_2\|} = \frac{1}{\frac{2}{5}}\begin{bmatrix} -\frac{8}{25} \\ \frac{6}{25} \end{bmatrix} = \frac{5}{2}\begin{bmatrix} -\frac{8}{25} \\ \frac{6}{25} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{4}{5} \\ \frac{3}{5} \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Calculate the entries of <m>R</m>:
                  <md>
                    <mrow>r_{11} \amp = \|\mathbf{f}_1\| = 5</mrow>
                    <mrow>r_{12} \amp = \mathbf{c}_2 \cdot \mathbf{q}_1 = 1 \cdot \frac{3}{5} + 2 \cdot \frac{4}{5} = \frac{3+8}{5} = \frac{11}{5}</mrow>
                    <mrow>r_{22} \amp = \|\mathbf{f}_2\| = \frac{2}{5}</mrow>
                  </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  Therefore, <m>A = QR</m> where:
                  <me>Q = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{3}{5} \amp -\frac{4}{5} \\ \frac{4}{5} \amp \frac{3}{5} \end{bmatrix} \quad 
                    R = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp \frac{11}{5} \\ 0 \amp \frac{2}{5} \end{bmatrix}</me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </activity>

              <activity>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Find the QR factorization of the matrix
                    <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
                  </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    The columns of <m>A</m> are <m>\mathbf{c}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{c}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <m>\mathbf{f}_1 = \mathbf{c}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, <m>\|\mathbf{f}_1\| = 6</m>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <m>\mathbf{q}_1 = \frac{\mathbf{f}_1}{\|\mathbf{f}_1\|} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <m>\mathbf{c}_2 \cdot \mathbf{q}_1 = 2 \cdot 1 + 3 \cdot 0 = 2</m>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <m>\mathbf{f}_2 = \mathbf{c}_2 - (\mathbf{c}_2 \cdot \mathbf{q}_1)\mathbf{q}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} - 2\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <m>\|\mathbf{f}_2\| = 3</m>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <m>\mathbf{q}_2 = \frac{\mathbf{f}_2}{\|\mathbf{f}_2\|} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Therefore, <m>A = QR</m> where:
                    <me>Q = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \quad
                      R = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</me>
                    </p>
                  </solution>
                </activity>

                <theorem>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Every square, invertible matrix <m>A</m> can be written as <m>A = QR</m>, where <m>Q</m> is an orthogonal matrix, and <m>R</m> is an upper triangular matrix with positive diagonal entries.
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                </theorem>
              </subsection>
            </section>
